  <brief_title>Cortisol Measurement During Intravenous Access With a Medical Clown</brief_title>
  <official_title>Level of Cortisol in Stress Response During Intravenous Access in the Pediatric Emergency Department With a Medical Clown: a Randomized Prospective Pilot Study</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Tel-Aviv Sourasky Medical Center</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Tel-Aviv Sourasky Medical Center</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The purpose of this study is to determine whether the presence of a medical clown in a
      pediatric emergency department procedure room would reduce children's anxiety. The
      investigators hypothesize that this positive influence will be expressed as lower levels of
      the stress hormone (Cortisol) in the blood.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
